revision.text:
The '''993–994 carbon-14 spike''' was a rapid increase in [[carbon-14]] content from tree rings, and followed the [[774–775 carbon-14 spike]].<ref name="Miyake_2013">{{cite web |url=http://www.nature.com/articles/ncomms2783 |title=Another rapid event in the carbon-14 content of tree rings : Nature Communications : Nature Publishing Group |date=2013  |author= Miyake, F. |display-authors=etal}}</ref> This event is also confirmed by a sharp increase of [[beryllium-10]] and hence considered as solar-origin. <ref name="Mekhaldi_2015">{{cite web |url=http://www.nature.com/articles/ncomms9611 |title=Multiradionuclide evidence for the solar origin of the cosmic-ray events of ᴀᴅ 774/5 and 993/4 : Nature Communications : Nature Publishing Group |date=2015 |author= Mekhaldi, F. |display-authors=etal}}</ref> It may have come from a massive [[Geomagnetic storm|solar storm]] as a series of auroral observations are known to be observed in late 992. <ref name="Hayakawa_2017">{{cite web |url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs11207-016-1039-2 |title=Historical Auroras in the 990s: Evidence of Great Magnetic Storms : Solar Physics : Springer |date=2017 |author= Hayakawa, H. |display-authors=etal}}</ref>

