'''Accarezzevole''' {{IPA-it|akkaretˈtseːvole|}} ([[Italian language|Italian]]: "Fawningly"<ref>{{cite CEM|wstitle=Accarezzevole}}</ref>) is a [[musical terminology|music term]] that is marked on [[sheet music]] to indicate a piece is to be played in an expressive and caressing manner.<ref>{{cite book |title= Elson's Pocket Music Dictionary|last= Elson|first= Louis|authorlink= |coauthors= |year= 1909|publisher= [[Oliver Ditson and Company]]|location= [[New York City]]|isbn= |page= |pages= |url= }}</ref> [[Alexander Scriabin]] was one of the few composers to use this term in his music.<ref>{{cite web| last =Attwood| first =Koji| authorlink =| coauthors =| title =Scriabin, Extensive Biography| work =| publisher =The Piano Society| date =| url =http://www.pianosociety.com/cms/index.php?section=634| format =| doi =| accessdate =28 January 2009| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20081113230025/http://pianosociety.com/cms/index.php?section=634| archive-date =2008-11-13| dead-url =yes| df =}}</ref>

