[[Category:Education literature]] [[Category:Education books]] [[Category:Women and education]] [[Category:Science education]] [[Category:Popular science books]] [[Category:Educational materials]] [[Category:United States educational programs]] [[Category:University of California, San Diego|San Diego, California]] [[Category:Organizations established in 2001]]

'''Vitrified forts''' are stone enclosures whose walls have been subjected to [[vitrification]] through heat.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.brigantesnation.com/VitrifiedForts/VitrifieedForts.htm |title=Vitrification of Hill Forts |accessdate=2008-01-24}}</ref> It was long thought that these structures were unique to Scotland, but they have since been identified in several other parts of western and northern Europe.

Vitrified forts are generally situated on hills offering strong defensive positions. Their form seems to have been determined by the contour of the flat summits which they enclose. The walls vary in size, a few being upwards of {{convert|12|ft}} high, and are so broad that they present the appearance of [[levee|embankments]]. Weak parts of the defence are strengthened by double or triple walls, and occasionally vast lines of [[rampart (fortification)|ramparts]], composed of large blocks of unhewn and unvitrified stones, envelop the vitrified centre at some distance from it.<ref name="EB1911">{{EB1911|inline=y|wstitle=Vitrified Forts |volume=28 |pages=149–150 |first=Robert |last=Munro |authorlink=Robert Munro (archaeologist)}}</ref> The walls themselves are termed vitrified ramparts.<ref>Darvill, Timothy (2008). ''Oxford Concise Dictionary of Archaeology'', 2nd ed., Oxford University Press, Oxford and New York, p. 376. {{ISBN|978-0-19-953404-3}}.</ref>

No [[lime (mineral)|lime]] or [[cement]] has been found in any of these structures, all of them presenting the peculiarity of being more or less consolidated by the fusion of the rocks of which they are built. This fusion, which has been caused by the application of intense heat, is not equally complete in the various forts, or even in the walls of the same fort. In some cases the stones are only partially melted and [[calcined]]; in others their adjoining edges are fused so that they are firmly cemented together; in many instances pieces of rock are enveloped in a glassy enamel-like coating which binds them into a uniform whole; and at times, though rarely, the entire length of the wall presents one solid mass of vitreous substance.<ref name="EB1911"/>

It is not clear why or how the walls were subjected to vitrification. Some [[antiquarian]]s have argued that it was done to strengthen the wall, but the heating actually weakens the structure. Battle damage is also unlikely to be the cause, as the walls are thought to have been subjected to carefully maintained fires to ensure they were hot enough for vitrification to take place.<ref>[http://archaeology.about.com/od/vterms/g/vitrified_forts.htm Vitrification temperatures]</ref><ref>[http://www.benderloch.org.uk/forum/viewtopic.php?f=7&t=1139 More information and the vitrification debate]</ref>

Most archaeologists now consider that vitrified forts are the product of deliberate destruction either following the capture of the site by an enemy force or by the occupants at the end of its active life as an act of ritual closure.<ref name="Ralston_143">Ralston 2006, 143-63{{full citation needed|date=December 2015}}</ref> The process has no chronological significance and is found during both Iron Age and Early Medieval Forts in Scotland.<ref name="Ralston_143"/>

Since [[John Williams (geologist)|John Williams]], one of the earliest of British [[geologist]]s, and author of ''The Natural History of the Mineral Kingdom'', first described these singular ruins in 1777, over 70 examples have been discovered in [[Scotland]].<ref name="EB1911"/> The most remarkable are:
*Dun Mac Sniachan (or [[Dun]] Mac Uisneachan), Argyll, the largest in area{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} at 245 m by 50 m.
*[[Benderloch]], north of [[Oban]]; {{gbmapping|NM 902 381}}
[[File:Mur vitrifié Ste-Suzanne.JPG|320px|thumb|right|Part of the vitrified wall at [[Sainte-Suzanne, Mayenne|Sainte-Suzanne]] ([[Mayenne]])]]
[[File:Mur vitrifié 2.JPG|320px|thumb|right|Fragment of vitrified wall at [[Sainte-Suzanne, Mayenne|Sainte-Suzanne]] ([[Mayenne]])]]
*Craig Phadraig, or Phadrick, near [[Inverness]]; {{gbmappingsmall|NH 640 452}}
*Ord Hill, North Kessock, near [[Inverness]]; {{gbmappingsmall|NH 664 491}};
*Dun Deardail (or Dundbhairdghall) in [[Glen Nevis]]; {{gbmappingsmall|NN 127 701}};
*Knock Farril (or Knockfarrel), near [[Strathpeffer]], {{gbmappingsmall|NH 505 585}};
*Dun Creich, in [[Sutherland]], {{gbmappingsmall|NH 651 882}};
*Finavon (or Finhaven), near [[Aberlemno]] {{gbmappingsmall|NO 507 556}};
*Barryhill, in [[Perthshire]];
*Laws, near [[Dundee]], {{gbmappingsmall|NO 490 349}};
*[[Dunagoil]] and [[Burnt Islands]], in [[County of Bute|Buteshire]];
*Mote of Mark, (Rockcliffe) near [[Rockcliffe, Dumfries and Galloway|Rockcliffe]], {{gbmappingsmall|NX 845 540}};
*Anwoth, (Trusty's Hill) near [[Gatehouse of Fleet]], {{gbmappingsmall|NX 589 560}};
*[[Tap o' Noth]], [[Aberdeenshire]]; {{gbmappingsmall|NJ 484 293}};
*[[Dunnideer Castle]], Aberdeenshire, Aberdeenshire,
*Cowdenknowes, in [[Berwickshire]], {{gbmappingsmall|NT 585 370}}.

For a long time it was supposed that these forts were peculiar to Scotland; but they are found also in the Isle of Man (Cronk Sumark) [[County Londonderry]] and [[County Cavan]], Ireland; in [[Upper Lusatia]], [[Bohemia]], [[Silesia]], [[Saxony]], and [[Thuringia]]; in the provinces on the [[Rhine]], especially in the neighbourhood of the [[Nahe (Rhine)|Nahe]]; in the [[Uecker|Ucker Lake]]; in Brandenburg, where the walls are formed of burnt and smelted [[brick]]s; in Hungary; in several places in France, such as Châteauvieux (near [[Pionnat]]), Péran, [[La Courbe]], [[Sainte-Suzanne, Mayenne|Sainte-Suzanne]], [[Puy de Gaudy]], and [[Thauron]]; also rarely in the north of England. [[Broborg|Barksdale]] is a vitrified hill-fort in [[Uppland]], Sweden.<ref name="EB1911"/>

==Appearance in Media==
===''[[Arthur C. Clarke's Mysterious World]]''===
The 16 September 1980 episode of this series features a segment in which the archaeologist Ian Ralston examines the mystery of the vitrified fort Tap o' Noth and tries to recreate how it might be accomplished by piling stones and setting a massive bonfire, repeating the work of [[V. Gordon Childe]] and [[Wallace Thorneycroft]] in the 1930s.<ref>[[Arthur C. Clarke|Clarke, A. C]], Welfare, S and Fairley, J. ''[[Arthur C. Clarke's Mysterious World]]''. Collins, 1980, p.61.</ref> The experiment produced a few partially vitrified stones, but no answers were gleaned as to how large-scale forts could have been crafted with the approach tried in the programme.<ref>''Arthur C. Clarke's Mysterious World'' ([[Yorkshire Television]] 1980; episode 3: "Ancient Wisdom" ([[Network DVD]] 7952792). Segment runs from 10:58 to 17:150</ref>

